Fulton Street, at the N.E. corner of Johnson Street, showing a view of a lunch wagon under the Fulton Street Elevated Lines of the B.M.T. This type of eating place, usually stationary, is popularly called a "diner". June 2, 1931.

P. L. Sperr.

Johnson Street, south side, east from Fulton Street, showing the Brooklyn Eagle Building, at the S.E. corner of Johnson and Washington Streets. In the background, is seen the Myrtle Ave., Elevated Line running here on Adams Street.

June 6, 1933.

P. L. Sperr.

Fulton Street (left), north from Johnson Street, showing the area extending east to Washington Street (right, view 4), which the W. P. A. is constructing into a new and wider approach to the Brooklyn Bridge. This project necessitated the razing of many buildings. On the left is the Fulton Street "El" and the loop, above Tillary Street, leading to the elevated car yards on Washington Street.

Views 1,2: October, 1936
Views 3,4: November, 1936
